# Verify DVWA

Objective: Ensure DVWA is running correctly.

Steps:
Start Docker (if needed).
Verify the container is running.
Open DVWA in your browser.
Log in.
Set the security level to Low.

Commands:
docker ps
docker start <container_id>
docker logs <container_id>

# Understand the HTTP Request

Objective: See how the browser communicates with DVWA.

Steps:
Open the SQL Injection page.
Enable Intercept in Burp Suite.
Submit a normal request.

Observe:
HTTP Method
URL
Query parameters
Cookies
Headers
Deliverables
Screenshot of intercepted request
Notes describing each part of the request

#Analyze the Response

Objective: Understand how the server responds.

Observe:

Status code
Content-Length
Response body
Cookies
Server header
Deliverables
Screenshot
Response analysis

# Compare DVWA Security Levels

Repeat the same workflow using:
Low
Medium
High

Record:
Input validation differences
Error messages
Application behavior
Security improvements

# Burp Repeater

Objective: Learn how Repeater works.

Steps:
Send the intercepted request to Repeater.
Resend the request.
Modify only non-sensitive values (for example, change a normal numeric ID to another valid numeric ID).
Observe how the response changes.

Deliverables:
Original request
Modified request
Comparison notes

# Read the DVWA Source Code

DVWA provides the vulnerable PHP code.

Look for:
User input
SQL query construction
Database function used
Validation (or lack of validation)

# SQLMap Detection (Authorized Lab Only)

Objective: Learn how an automated scanner identifies SQL injection.

Against your local DVWA:
Run SQLMap against the vulnerable page.
Read its output.

Identify:
Database type
Injectable parameter
Risk level
Recommended next steps

# Browser Developer Tools

Open Developer Tools (F12).

Inspect:
Network tab
Request headers
Response headers
Cookies
Query parameters

Compare them with Burp Suite.

# Compare GET vs POST

Use two DVWA pages that submit data differently.

Observe:
URL
Request body
Headers
Parameters

